"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794045","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-28","<p>There have been 4 occasions where the Fire Service has been required to enter HMP Berwyn since opening in Spring 2017. All fires were extinguished by the time the fire service arrived at Berwyn.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-28T17:40:14.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794045/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794045/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794045/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-22","Berwyn Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on how many occasions the North Wales Fire and Rescue Service has been called to HM Prison Berwyn since that prison opened in Spring 2017.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","115133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794046","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-28","<p>Since opening in Spring 2017, a total of 69 men have attended the local Accident and Emergency department at Wrexham Maelor Hospital.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-28T17:37:09.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794046/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794046/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794046/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-22","Berwyn Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners from HM Prison Berwyn have attended accident and emergency departments at local district general hospitals since that prison opened in Spring 2017.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","115134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794047","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-11-28T16:13:59.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794047/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794047/answer","PQ 115135.pdf","PQ 115135.pdf","UKSA response","UKSA response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794047/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-22","Low Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the change has been in the number of people employed full-time and earning less than £11,000 per annum from January (a) 2012 to (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","115135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794048","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-29","<p>The Ministry of Justice and <em>Her Majesty's Prison and Probation Service (HM</em>PPS) takes seriously the ongoing challenges that substance misuse, including psychoactive substances (PS) pose to our establishments and we continue to implement a range of measures to address both the availability and use of such harmful substances. This is based on a multi-agency approach working closely with health partners and law enforcement agencies.</p><p> </p><p>The HMPPS Incident Reporting System does not specifically record the reasons behind an incident and therefore it is not possible to provide the information requested.</p><p> </p><p>Prisons have at their disposal a range of security measures to reduce the supply of drugs into prisons including physical searching, the use of x-ray machines, CCTV surveillance cameras, intelligence-led searches as well as drug detection dogs. HMPPS have trained more than 300 dogs to detect PS and these dogs are available to all prisons. HMPPS are also exploring additional innovative security measures and new technology to complement existing searching methods in prisons.</p><p> </p><p>The introduction of mandatory drug testing for psychoactive substances in prisons in September 2016 was also a significant step to support our prisons in tackling the supply and use of these lethal drugs. We are not aware of any other prison service in the world that has introduced these innovative new tests.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-29T16:49:59.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794048/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794048/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794048/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-22","Berwyn Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many incidents relating to Spice have been recorded at HM Prison Berwyn since that prison opened in Spring 2017.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","115136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794049","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-29","<p>I hold a range of meetings with farmers, food producers and environmentalists from across the UK on a variety of issues, including how to embed good environmental practices in farming. I will continue to engage widely and with the devolved administrations as we deliver on our manifesto commitment to develop a new environmental land management system. As set out in our manifesto, this is to be introduced in the next parliament.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-29T17:36:33.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794049/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794049/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794049/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-22","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will hold discussions with farming representatives and environmental groups on how to ensure workable environmental practices on UK farms.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","115137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794050","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-30","<p>The additional funding from the Reserve in 18/19 and 19/20 is being set aside to ensure funding is available as required. HMT will work with departments and DExEU over the coming weeks to refine estimates of departmental requirements and will allocate 18/19 funding in early 2018. Departmental allocations for 2019-20 will be agreed later in 2018-19. Departmental allocations from the Reserve will be set out at Supplementary Estimates in the relevant year as is usual.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-11-30T16:38:41.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794050/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794050/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794050/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-22","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to page 22 of Autumn Budget 2017, how the £3 billion set aside to prepare for the UK leaving the EU will be allocated across (a) government departments and (b) public authorities.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","115138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794051","Home Office","false","2017-11-29","<p>While the independent Crime Survey for England and Wales continues to show that, for those crimes covered by the Survey, people in rural areas are less likely to be the victims of crime than those in urban areas, we do recognise the impact that crime can have on rural communities. However, it is for chief constables and Police and Crime Commissioners, as operational leaders and elected local representatives, to decide how best to deploy resources to manage and respond to crime, in both rural and urban areas alike.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-29T17:18:44.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794051/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794051/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794051/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-22","Crime: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her strategy is to combat rural crime during the 2017 Parliament.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","115139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794052","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-30","<p>The £700m of additional funding already allocated includes £412m of additional funding that DIT, FCO and DExEU received over the parliament that was set out at Autumn Statement 2016. In addition, the Treasury has also allocated £250m from the Reserve to a number of departments in 17/18. Departmental allocations from the 17/18 Reserve will be set out at Supplementary Estimates, in the usual way.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-11-30T16:37:37.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794052/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794052/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-22","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to page 22 of Autumn Budget 2017, how the £700 million already allocated to prepare for the UK leaving the EU has been allocated across (a) government departments and (b) public authorities.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","115140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794053","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-30","<p>The UK Government is concerned by any restrictions placed on Christians in China. The freedom to practise, change or share your faith or belief is a fundamental human right that all people should enjoy. I am alarmed to hear that Christians may have been prevented from leaving the country on the basis of their religion or to attend a religious event and my officials are seeking further information.</p><p>The UK Government has raised these concerns about restrictions on freedom of religion or belief directly with the Chinese authorities at the UK-China Human Rights Dialogue in Beijing on 27 June. We also issued an item IV statement at the 35th UN Human Rights Council in June and will raise the latest matter at the earliest future opportunity.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-11-30T17:28:46.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794053/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794053/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-22","China: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to his Chinese counterpart on the case of Christians prevented from leaving that country to attend a Protestant Reformation event in Jakarta, Indonesia, on 14 November.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","115141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794054","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-30","<p>By supporting locally led projects, the Government's Local Full Fibre Networks (LFFN) programme aims to stimulate commercial investment in full fibre. This is the gold standard of broadband and will deliver connections capable of gigabit speeds, far beyond ultrafast.</p><p><br> On 22 November 2017, the Chancellor of the Exchequer opened the £190 million LFFN Challenge Fund for local bodies to bid from, for projects that aim to stimulate commercial investment in gigabit capable infrastructure across the UK, including in rural areas</p><p> </p><p>Over the summer, we received expressions of interest in the LFFN Programme from a number of local bodies in Northern Ireland:</p><ul><li>Antrim and Newtownabbey Borough Council;</li><li>Ards and North Down Borough Council;</li><li>Armagh City Council,</li><li>Banbridge and Craigavon Borough Council;</li><li>Belfast City Council</li><li>Causeway Coast and Glens Borough Council;</li><li>Derry City and Strabane District Council;</li><li>Fermanagh and Omagh District Council;</li><li>Lisburn and Castlereagh City Council;</li><li>Mid and East Antrim Borough Council; Mid Ulster District Council;</li><li>Newry, Mourne and Down District Council</li></ul><p><br> We look forward to bids from local bodies in Northern Ireland now that the Challenge Fund is open.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-11-30T15:34:47.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794054/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794054/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-22","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what progress she is making on securing maximum ultra-fast broadband access in rural areas.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","115142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794055","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>As Carillion is a strategic supplier to Government, they have been assigned a Crown Representative.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-11-28T16:06:12.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794055/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794055/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-22","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether a Crown Representative has been assigned to Carillion.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","115143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794056","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-29","<p>DFID led the development of the new HMG Strategic Coherence of ODA-funded Research (SCOR) Board within the UK Collaborative for Development Sciences UKCDS (DFID is the major funder of UKCDS). SCOR has been established as a cross-HMG mechanism to ensure that UK’s ODA-funded science and research is coherent across HMG departments and is having maximum impact on international development objectives and outcomes in developing countries.</p><p>The Board’s first meeting was held on the 17 Nov 2017. DFID is represented on by Board through the departmental Chief Scientific Adviser who is also responsible for DFID research budget. The SCOR Board is planning to meet four times in 2018, starting in January.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","115145","2017-11-29T17:05:16.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794056/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794056/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-22","Overseas Aid: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the remit and objectives of the Strategic Coherence of ODA-funded Research Board are.","false","Biography information for Martin Whitfield","East Lothian","Martin Whitfield","115144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794057","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-29","<p>DFID led the development of the new HMG Strategic Coherence of ODA-funded Research (SCOR) Board within the UK Collaborative for Development Sciences UKCDS (DFID is the major funder of UKCDS). SCOR has been established as a cross-HMG mechanism to ensure that UK’s ODA-funded science and research is coherent across HMG departments and is having maximum impact on international development objectives and outcomes in developing countries.</p><p>The Board’s first meeting was held on the 17 Nov 2017. DFID is represented on by Board through the departmental Chief Scientific Adviser who is also responsible for DFID research budget. The SCOR Board is planning to meet four times in 2018, starting in January.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","115144","2017-11-29T17:05:16.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794057/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794057/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-22","Overseas Aid: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, when the Strategic Coherence for ODA-funded Research Board first plans to meet and how often it will do so.","false","Biography information for Martin Whitfield","East Lothian","Martin Whitfield","115145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794058","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-30","<p>The UK supports the full implementation of the Algiers Accord of 2015 which cites respect for religious freedom as one of its core principles. In addition the UK has supported a Community Reconciliation and Peacebuilding Project for the past three financial years, which works with communities, including mixed faith communities, in Mali to promote mutual understanding and reduce conflict.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-11-30T16:47:05.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794058/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794058/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-22","Mali: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs what recent steps he has taken to promote freedom of religion and belief in Mali.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","115146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794059","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-28","<p>The Government will create the UK Shared Prosperity Fund to boost productivity and reduce economic inequality across the country following our departure from the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>As announced in the Industrial Strategy white paper, the Government will consult widely on the design of the new Fund in 2018. We will work with devolved administrations prior to public consultation.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-28T16:40:59.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794059/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794059/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-22","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy what plans the Government has made on its plans for a UK Shared Prosperity Fund; what the Government's planned timeframe is for (a) the whole introduction of the fund and (b) introducing draft legislation; what he plans the scope of that fund will be; and what consultation and input in plans to seek from the devolved administrations on that fund.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","115147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794060","Cabinet Office","false","2017-12-19","<p>We recognise the importance of managing relationships with Strategic Suppliers, including any risks to the operation of public services and the achievement value for money. Our Strategic Supplier Risk Management Policy has been published on GOV.UK:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/80222/20121108_Strategic_Supplier_Risk_Management_Policy.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/80222/20121108_Strategic_Supplier_Risk_Management_Policy.pdf</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-12-19T15:48:53.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794060/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794060/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-22","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the risk of a strategic supplier to the Government folding on the (a) the operation of public services and (b) value for money.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","115148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794061","Department for Education","false","2017-11-30","<p>The Erasmus+ programme was introduced in 2014. Data on the number of participants broken down by sector and across the UK is available at <a href="https://www.erasmusplus.org.uk/statistics-0" target="_blank">https://www.erasmusplus.org.uk/statistics-0</a>.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-11-30T09:03:54.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794061/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794061/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-22","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of people who have been participants in the Erasmus  Plus programme since its introduction in each (a) region of the UK and (b) sector.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","115149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794062","Prime Minister","false","2017-11-27","<p>I promised in the wake of the appalling atrocity in Manchester that this Government would do all it can to help victims recover and the city to heal. A taskforce has been established within the Cabinet Office to oversee progress and expedite payments when necessary to ensure that Manchester gets the financial support it needs.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-11-27T17:01:28.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794062/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794062/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-11-22","Terrorism: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, pursuant to her oral Answer of Wednesday 15 November 2017, Official Report, column 366, when she plans to announce the amount of funding which will be allocated to Greater Manchester to manage the aftermath of the terrorist attack at the Manchester Arena; and when she plans to make that funding available.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","115150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794063","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-28","<p>As we leave the EU we have a great opportunity to reshape policies to meet our national priorities. We are considering the longer term approach to the EU school milk scheme in the context of our domestic schemes. Any future changes in this area will be subject to wide consultation with stakeholders.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-28T14:51:46.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794063/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794063/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-22","School Milk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when he plans to begin discussions on a new domestic school milk subsidy programme to replace the current EU Scheme.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","115151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794064","Department for Education","false","2017-11-28","<p>The 2016 Budget announced funding for a number of programmes linked to the revenue from the Soft Drinks Industry Levy. The department will receive £575 million during the current spending review period, which will be used to:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Double funding for the primary physical education and Sport Premium to £320 million a year from 2017. The Department for Education and the Department of Health contribute £100 million and £60 million per year to the premium respectively, with the Soft Drinks Levy funding contributing £415 million over the remainder of the current spending review period, table attached.</li><li>Provide £100 million in 2018/19 for a new healthy pupils capital fund.</li><li>Provide £60 million to other relevant projects, for example breakfast clubs (£26 million over the next three years) and essential life skills programme.</li></ul><p> </p><p>Expected revenue from the levy during the Spending Review period is £550 million for the UK as a whole. The total funding provided for these programmes in England is £575 million. In addition, the devolved administrations will continue to benefit in full from the Barnett formula arising from the levy-funded spending package announced at the 2016 Budget.</p><p> </p><p>We announced in February 2017 that the healthy pupils capital programme will build on the government’s plans for schools to provide a longer school day, by changing the focus of the scheme to provide new facilities or improve existing ones to make it easier for a range of extra-curricular activities to be provided.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","115565","2017-11-28T16:48:17.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794064/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794064/answer","115152, 115565 Table.docx","115152, 115565 Table.docx","Funding for the premium from the soft drinks levy","Funding for the premium from the soft drinks levy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794064/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-22","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will provide (a) breakdown of forecast expenditure of the proceeds of the Soft Drinks Industry Levy for  (i)  2017-18, (ii) 2018-19 and (iii) 2019/20; and (b) unallocated funding for those years.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","115152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794065","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-27","<p>We are committed to working with stakeholders to improve the scheme, and recently carried out reforms to the Social Fund Funeral Expenses Regulations, to clarify eligibility and simplify the application process. The formal government response can be accessed <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/656887/consultation-response-reforms-to-funeral-expenses-payments.pdf" target="_blank">here</a>, these regulations will come into force from spring 2018.</p><p>Funeral Expenses Payments continue to cover the necessary costs involved with funerals and cremations, and up to £700 for other funeral expenses. The funding offered from both Social Fund Funeral Expenses Payments and Social Fund Budgeting Loans offers an adequate level of support whilst maintaining a fiscally viable fund.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-11-27T16:08:11.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794065/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794065/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-22","Funerals: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what progress he has made with respect to paragraph 17 of the Second Special Report of Session 2016-17 of the Work and Pensions Committee, Support for the bereaved: Government response to the Committee’s Ninth Report of Session 2015-16, HC230.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","115153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794066","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-27","<p>In April 2015, the government introduced a charge on non-residents’ gains on the direct disposal of UK residential property.</p><p> </p><p>At Autumn Budget 2017, the government announced that a charge would be extended to gains made on disposals of all UK residential and commercial property by non-residents, including disposals made indirectly through the sale of shares in a property rich company.</p><p> </p><p>A technical consultation was launched at Budget. This is focused on the detailed implementation of this policy, and does not solicit views on wider changes to the UK property tax regime.</p><p> </p><p>It is the government’s policy that all double taxation treaties should permit gains on the direct and indirect disposal of UK immovable property to be taxed in the UK. An avoidance rule was introduced with immediate effect from Autumn Budget 2017 to prevent non-residents from abusing existing treaties to avoid the new charge.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","115156 ; 115157 ; 115158","2017-11-27T17:27:06.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794066/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794066/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-22","Tax Avoidance: Luxembourg","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether it is his policy that gains made by non UK residents on sales of UK immovable property which are held by offshore companies held by Luxembourg companies will be subject to UK tax.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","115154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794067","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-27","<p>We continue to liaise with the Scottish Government on its plans to introduce its own funeral expenses assistance scheme in summer 2019.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-11-27T16:10:11.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794067/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794067/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-22","Funerals: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what progress has he made with respect to paragraph 18 of the Second Special Report of Session 2016-17 of the Work and Pensions Committee, Support for the bereaved: Government response to the Committee’s Ninth Report of Session 2015-16, HC230.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","115155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794068","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-27","<p>In April 2015, the government introduced a charge on non-residents’ gains on the direct disposal of UK residential property.</p><p> </p><p>At Autumn Budget 2017, the government announced that a charge would be extended to gains made on disposals of all UK residential and commercial property by non-residents, including disposals made indirectly through the sale of shares in a property rich company.</p><p> </p><p>A technical consultation was launched at Budget. This is focused on the detailed implementation of this policy, and does not solicit views on wider changes to the UK property tax regime.</p><p> </p><p>It is the government’s policy that all double taxation treaties should permit gains on the direct and indirect disposal of UK immovable property to be taxed in the UK. An avoidance rule was introduced with immediate effect from Autumn Budget 2017 to prevent non-residents from abusing existing treaties to avoid the new charge.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","115154 ; 115157 ; 115158","2017-11-27T17:27:06.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794068/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794068/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-22","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Autumn 2017, whether he is consulting on how to ensure non UK residents are not able to avoid paying tax on gains made by the sale of immovable property by declaring these disposals as indirect.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","115156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794069","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-27","<p>In April 2015, the government introduced a charge on non-residents’ gains on the direct disposal of UK residential property.</p><p> </p><p>At Autumn Budget 2017, the government announced that a charge would be extended to gains made on disposals of all UK residential and commercial property by non-residents, including disposals made indirectly through the sale of shares in a property rich company.</p><p> </p><p>A technical consultation was launched at Budget. This is focused on the detailed implementation of this policy, and does not solicit views on wider changes to the UK property tax regime.</p><p> </p><p>It is the government’s policy that all double taxation treaties should permit gains on the direct and indirect disposal of UK immovable property to be taxed in the UK. An avoidance rule was introduced with immediate effect from Autumn Budget 2017 to prevent non-residents from abusing existing treaties to avoid the new charge.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","115154 ; 115156 ; 115158","2017-11-27T17:27:06.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794069/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794069/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-22","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if the Government will extend its consultation on tax gains made by non UK residents on UK immovable property sales to include applying stamp duty land tax to offshore investors who hold real estate through special purpose offshore companies and sell shares in those companies.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","115157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794070","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-27","<p>In April 2015, the government introduced a charge on non-residents’ gains on the direct disposal of UK residential property.</p><p> </p><p>At Autumn Budget 2017, the government announced that a charge would be extended to gains made on disposals of all UK residential and commercial property by non-residents, including disposals made indirectly through the sale of shares in a property rich company.</p><p> </p><p>A technical consultation was launched at Budget. This is focused on the detailed implementation of this policy, and does not solicit views on wider changes to the UK property tax regime.</p><p> </p><p>It is the government’s policy that all double taxation treaties should permit gains on the direct and indirect disposal of UK immovable property to be taxed in the UK. An avoidance rule was introduced with immediate effect from Autumn Budget 2017 to prevent non-residents from abusing existing treaties to avoid the new charge.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","115154 ; 115156 ; 115157","2017-11-27T17:27:06.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794070/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794070/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-22","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps to prevent people from avoiding capital gains tax and corporation tax paid by non UK residents on UK immovable property by using the provisions of double taxation treaties.","false","Biography information for Stella Creasy","Walthamstow","Stella Creasy","115158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794071","Home Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>The Home Office replied to the letter from the Hon Member about Mr Shamus Ud Din on 22 November. Your MP Account Manager has supplied a further copy of this reply to your office on the 23 November.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-28T18:02:52.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794071/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/794071/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-22","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for what reason her Department has not yet responded to the correspondence from the hon Member for Ross, Skye and Lochaber in relation to Mr Shamus Ud Din.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","115159"
