"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792968","Home Office","false","2017-11-27","<p>The Inquiry is delivering in accordance with the work plan it published in December 2016. Details about the Inquiry's work are published by the Inquiry on its website - <a href="http://www.iicsa.org.uk" target="_blank">www.iicsa.org.uk</a></p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2017-11-27T17:30:53.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792968/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792968/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-21","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent progress has been made on the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","114753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792969","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-29","<p>The Department is currently in the process of setting up the carbon capture usage &amp; storage (CCUS) Task Force and we expect the task force to deliver a plan to Government on deploying CCUS cost effectively in the UK summer 2018. Details of its membership and terms of reference will be published on the Department’s website in January 2018.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-11-29T16:55:06.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792969/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792969/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-21","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when the CCUS Cost Challenge Task Force will be established; and whether the terms of reference will be made public.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","114754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792970","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-27","<p>The Government’s Clean Growth Strategy confirms that the Government’s ambition is to deploy carbon capture usage and storage (CCUS) at scale during the 2030s, subject to costs coming down sufficiently. The Government will publish a deployment pathway for CCUS in 2018, informed by the CCUS Cost Challenge Task Force, which will set out the steps needed achieve this ambition.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-11-27T14:17:33.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792970/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792970/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-21","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 13 November 2017 to Question 111997, on carbon capture and storage, at what level the Government's ambition will be set for deploying carbon capture usage and storage during the 2030s.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","114755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792971","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-27","<p>The Department is in the final stages of setting up the Ministerial-led carbon capture usage and storage (CCUS) Council. I will be chairing the Council and it will involve senior representatives from across the CCUS sector. The role of the Council will be to advise the Department on the progress made in progressing the Government’s new approach to CCUS and CCUS priorities and will meet two to three times a year.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-11-27T14:18:46.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792971/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792971/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-21","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when the Ministerial-led CCUS Council will be established; and when that Council is expected to provide its first report to the Government.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","114756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792972","Department of Health","false","2017-11-29","<p>GP at Hand is a practice that holds a General Medical Service contract. Practices are paid per weighted registered patient and, as patients register or de-register with GP at Hand, this will alter the payment to the practice. Funding follows the registered patients, so if patients are leaving their current practice for GP at Hand the funding will move to that practice. The practice list sizes are counted and payments adjusted on the first of each quarter and so any payment adjustments will be made in January.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-29T17:06:52.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792972/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792972/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-21","GP at Hand","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 20 November 2017 to Question 112428, what the cost of the GP at hand service has been to the public purse to date.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","114757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792973","Department of Health","false","2017-11-29","<p>GP at Hand is not a service that has been specifically commissioned by the Department or NHS England. It is a locally developed service commissioned by Hammersmith and Fulham Clinical Commissioning Group and operated by a general practice in London (Dr Jefferies and Partners) in collaboration with a private technology provider (Babylon).</p><p> </p><p>The Department and NHS England are following the development of the GP at Hand service to better understand how digital services can be adopted in a way that safeguards patients, delivers a quality service and supports the future sustainability of the National Health Service.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-29T17:09:06.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792973/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792973/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-21","GP at Hand","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department plans to rollout the GP at Hand service nationwide.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","114758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792974","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-29","<p>The Secretary of State has regular discussions with Transport for the North (TfN) and Transport for Greater Manchester (TfGM), where a range of issues are discussed.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s Rail investment and HS2 programmes will lead to improved connectivity for the Greater Manchester area, including Wigan, Warrington, Bolton and central Manchester. Leigh will benefit from this.</p><p> </p><p>TfGM are advancing their wider plans for connectivity across the city region through their Greater Manchester 2040 Transport Strategy and TfN has now been established as a statutory sub-national transport body to assess transport priorities in the region.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-29T10:22:47.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792974/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792974/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-21","Railways: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with (a) Transport for the North and (b) Transport for Greater Manchester on rail connectivity​ in Leigh; and what steps he is taking to improve rail connectivity in that region.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","114759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792975","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-28","<p>The Department for Transport has not made an assessment of the potential costs and benefits of installing a rail line and station to the town of Leigh.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s policy is that it is for local authorities and Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs) to determine the best way to meet local transport needs and take the first step in evaluating benefits and prioritising available resources. It would be for Transport for Greater Manchester to develop such plans and seek funding opportunities.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-28T11:40:11.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792975/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792975/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-21","Railways: Leigh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment​ his Department has made of the potential costs and benefits of installing a rail line and station to the town of Leigh.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","114760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792976","Department of Health","false","2017-11-29","<p>Placing a new, additional data collection requirement on National Health Service or local government organisations to track the duration of transfers of care for each individual patient would be disproportionate at this time. No one should stay in a hospital bed longer than necessary and the Government is committed to reducing delayed transfers of care (DToC). Information is collected monthly that allows progress against expectations for DToC reductions to be assessed.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-11-29T17:34:21.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792976/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792976/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-21","Patients: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 16 November 2017 Question 111963 on patients: transport, for what reasons his Department will not commit​ to monitor the average duration of transfers of care.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","114761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792977","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-01","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service has a programme of monthly inspections which are undertaken across the estate, including at Westminster Magistrates’ Court, to ensure compliance with the Equality Act 2010. Westminster Magistrates’ Court is currently compliant.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-12-01T10:54:10.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792977/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792977/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Magistrates' Courts: City of Westminster","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what monitoring his Department has in place to ensure that Westminster Magistrates Court is compliant with disability access legislation.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","114762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792978","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-28","<p>The Ministry of Justice grant funds the court based Witness Service for the provision of emotional and practical support to witnesses giving evidence in criminal courts in England and Wales. The Witness Service does not have a specific responsibility to provide drinking water in courts but has, in the past, put in place arrangements for the provision of drinking water in a number of witness waiting areas where they did not exist as this is an element of supporting witnesses as they prepare to give evidence.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-11-28T16:21:46.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792978/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792978/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Magistrates' Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for what reasons his Department uses the Witness Service to supply drinking water to victims at magistrates courts.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","114763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792979","Home Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>Significant progress has been made in taking decisions on applications affected by the MM Lebanon Supreme Court ruling and there remain very few applications awaiting assessment.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-23T17:30:43.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792979/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792979/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-21","Visas: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress UK Visas & Immigration has made on clearing the backlog of applications for spouse visas as a result of the Supreme Court ruling in February 2017.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","114764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792980","Home Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>The specific data requested is not published by the Home Office.</p><p>Published data on visa processing times, including the percentage of visas processed within published service standards, is published online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data</a> (then listed by publication date under ‘UK Visas &amp; Immigration’).</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-23T17:36:13.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792980/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792980/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-21","Visas: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average time is for applicants waiting for decisions on spouse visa applications.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","114765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792981","Home Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>The specific data requested is not published by the Home Office.</p><p>Published data on visa processing times, including the percentage of visas processed within published service standards, is published online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data</a> (then listed by publication date under ‘UK Visas &amp; Immigration’).</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-23T17:36:57.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792981/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792981/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-21","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how long the average wait time is for immigration applicants using the priority service.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","114766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792982","Home Office","false","2017-11-27","<p>Data for banking and credit card industry fraud are published by ONS on a quarterly basis. These data will cover frauds against individuals as well as industry bodies. The latest data are for year to June 2017 and are available in Table A5 at the link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesappendixtables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesappendixtables</a></p><p> </p><p>The way in which fraud offences are reported and subsequently recorded has changed in recent years. Previously, police forces were responsible for recording fraud offences, however, from April 2011 Action Fraud began gradually taking over the recording of fraud offences on behalf of individual police forces, completing in March 2013. Action Fraud is the UK’s national fraud and cybercrime reporting centre. The industry bodies Cifas and FFA UK also record data on fraud offences committed against their members.</p><p> </p><p>Information on fraud offences prior to the switch to Action Fraud can be found in Table A4 in the same link as provided above.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-11-27T17:36:08.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792982/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792982/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-21","Bank Services: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many acts of bank fraud against an individual were recorded in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","114767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792983","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-29","<p>The information requested is not held by the Treasury.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-11-29T16:49:05.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792983/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792983/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-21","Bank Services: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the conviction rate for bank fraud against an individual was in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","114768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792984","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-27","<p>We have made changes to how CRCs are paid for future years so they can focus on activities that best rehabilitate offenders and keep society safe. This additional investment will see projected payments to providers being no higher than originally budgeted for at the time of the reforms.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested can be found in the table below.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-27T17:29:48.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792984/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792984/answer","PQ 114769 Richard Burgon CRC Contract Values - Table.doc","PQ 114769 Richard Burgon CRC Contract Values - Table.doc","114769 - Table","114769 - Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792984/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State what the original estimated contract value was for each Community Rehabilitation Company contract; what the initial contract value was for each Community Rehabilitation Company prior to the interim agreement modifications; what the actual contract value was for each Community Rehabilitation Company before the second contract modifications; and what the contract value was for each Community Rehabilitation Company after the second modifications.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","114769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792985","Home Office","false","2017-11-27","<p>Published information on the number of applications for leave to remain in all categories, as well as data on UK Visa and Immigration performance against service standards for applications made in the UK and from overseas, and the proportion of those cases classified as non-straightforward, can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data%23uk-visas-and-immigration" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data#uk-visas-and-immigration</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Where an application is defined as non-straightforward due to complexity, the customer will be written to within the normal processing time to explain why it will not be decided within the normal standard, and to explain what will happen next.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","114771","2017-11-27T09:58:02.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792985/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792985/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-21","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications for leave to remain status in each category were submitted in 2016; and how many were resolved within six months.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","114770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792986","Home Office","false","2017-11-27","<p>Published information on the number of applications for leave to remain in all categories, as well as data on UK Visa and Immigration performance against service standards for applications made in the UK and from overseas, and the proportion of those cases classified as non-straightforward, can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data%23uk-visas-and-immigration" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/migration-transparency-data#uk-visas-and-immigration</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Where an application is defined as non-straightforward due to complexity, the customer will be written to within the normal processing time to explain why it will not be decided within the normal standard, and to explain what will happen next.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","114770","2017-11-27T09:58:02.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792986/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792986/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-21","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many cases for leave to remain status submitted in 2016 were designated as being as outside the service level agreement.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","114771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792987","Department of Health","false","2017-11-27","<p>No decision has been made about the timing of negotiations with industry on medicines pricing arrangements for 2019 onwards. The Department has regular and ongoing dialogue with patient representative groups about medicines pricing and access issues, and all those views will help to inform discussions between the industry and the Department on the new arrangements.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","114773","2017-11-27T16:41:41.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792987/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792987/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-21","Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the timetable is for the negotiations of the next Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","114772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792988","Department of Health","false","2017-11-27","<p>No decision has been made about the timing of negotiations with industry on medicines pricing arrangements for 2019 onwards. The Department has regular and ongoing dialogue with patient representative groups about medicines pricing and access issues, and all those views will help to inform discussions between the industry and the Department on the new arrangements.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","114772","2017-11-27T16:41:42.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792988/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792988/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792988/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-21","Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has to engage with patient groups on the contents of the next Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","114773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792989","Department of Health","false","2017-11-29","<p>Use of innovative medicines in England is reported through the innovation scorecard. The most recent publication was in October 2017 and is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB30106" target="_blank">https://digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB30106</a></p><p> </p><p>Since 2014, the medicines in the scorecard have changed as new medicines have become available. The scorecard shows that for the 12 months from April 2016 to March 2017, compared to the previous 12 months where comparable data is available, 73% of innovative medicines covered by the scorecard were prescribed more.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-29T14:40:57.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792989/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792989/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-21","Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the success of the Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme in ensuring patients can access the most effective and innovative medicines.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","114774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792990","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-29","<p>Environmental protections for designated areas continue as before, ensuring the whole body of existing EU environmental law continues to have effect in UK law.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State has also announced that we will consult on creating a new, statutory, independent body to uphold environmental standards, and a new policy statement setting out environmental principles.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to uphold all our obligations under international environmental treaties.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-11-29T17:29:37.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792990/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792990/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-21","Marine Protected Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has to ensure that marine Special Areas of Conservation and Special Protection Areas continue to receive the same level of environmental protection as currently received after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","114775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792991","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-27","<p>Lead Local Flood Authorities (LLFAs) are required to report on progress with their strategies on an annual basis and the last annual collection was as of 31 March 2017. Following this, I wrote in July to the outstanding authorities and as a result, as of the beginning of November 2017, out of the 152 in England:</p><p> </p><ol><li><p>143 have completed and published their strategy; and</p></li><li><p>9 have either completed their public consultation or were at public consultation stage on their draft.</p><p> </p></li></ol><p>The Department is continuing to monitor progress with the Lead Local Flood Authorities that have not yet completed their strategy.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-11-27T11:48:14.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792991/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792991/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-21","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many lead local flood authorities have (a) completed and (b) not completed a local flood risk management strategy.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","114776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792992","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-29","<p>​Since 2013 the Home Office and the FCO/BEIS Science &amp; Innovation Network in Beijing has continued to support China to bring an end to unnecessary cosmetics testing on animals, advising on a science based approach for alternative testing.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-11-29T14:21:17.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792992/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792992/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-21","Animal Experiments: Cosmetics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to encourage countries yet to do so to join the ban on cosmetics animal testing and the sale of animal-tested cosmetics.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","114777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792993","Department of Health","false","2017-11-29","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England advises that a postcode-level dataset that will enable the calculation of travel times to radiotherapy units is currently in development by the National Cancer Registry and Analysis Service. Results will be published in 2018.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-29T17:14:42.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792993/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792993/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-21","Radiotherapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, in which ten areas of England do residents have the longest travel times to their nearest radiotherapy units.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","114778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792994","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-27","<p>The Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy Select Committee are scrutinising the Government’s Draft Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill. The draft bill would require Ofgem to impose a cap on all standard variable and default tariffs, and defines a default tariff as a rate or amount charged for if the customer fails to choose an alternative rate.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-27T11:43:20.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792994/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792994/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-21","Energy: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his policy is on a cap for default tariffs which are not standard variable tariffs; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","114779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792995","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-12-11","<p>The Government estimates that there has been the following amount of capital spending on Flood and Coastal Erosion Risk Management projects in each year since 2010:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£million</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>399</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>298</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>296</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>358</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>522</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>450</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>502</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These figures include schemes costing below £100k, which were previously not geo-located, and include Capital costs, as well as capital investments spent on EA activities including the FCRM attributable to flood protection.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-12-11T15:09:52.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792995/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792995/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-21","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the cost of completed Flood and Coastal Erosion Risk Management (FCERM) projects across England in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","114780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792996","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-11-27","<p>The Government has always been clear that increased rates retention by local government would need to be matched and funded by equivalent devolution of new responsibilities or the ending of grants. The assessment of the overall level of funding for local government is a function of the Spending Review.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-11-27T14:59:46.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792996/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792996/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-11-21","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what consideration he has given to redistributing the share of business rates that central Government receives to help relieve financial pressures on local authorities.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","114781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792997","Home Office","false","2017-11-27","<p>The Home Office collects information from police forces on the number of police recorded offences that have been committed (in full or in part) online. The online flag became mandatory from April 2015 therefore data prior to this are not available.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of police recorded offences flagged as having an online element are published as experimental statistics in the ONS ‘Crime in England and Wales’ quarterly bulletins.</p><p> </p><p>These data can be found in table E4 of the experimental tables on the ONS website: <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesexperimentaltables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesexperimentaltables</a>.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-11-27T14:44:43.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792997/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792997/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-21","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate her department has made of the level of recorded cybercrime in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","114782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792998","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-27","<p>The cost of attending live sport for all ages is something that must be kept under constant review, and we support a fair deal for fans, but respect that ticket-pricing policies should remain a matter for event hosts.</p><p> </p><p>The Government's sport strategy, Sporting Future, recognises how attending live sporting events can benefit individuals, communities and the wider sporting economy. Ten major sporting events supported by UK Sport saw over 1.1 million people attend in 2017, including the IAAF World Championships in London, where over 100,000 children under 16 attended at a ticket price of £9.58, signifying Usain Bolt's 100m world record. The World Para Athletics Championships similarly saw over 100,000 schoolchildren attend, with 30,000 children being transported free of charge by Transport for London as part of a two session ring-fenced school project. The men's and women's World Series Triathlons held in Leeds in June also attracted over 50,000 spectators who were able to enjoy the events for free.</p><p> </p><p>Football clubs are also offering concessions on ticket prices and associated costs for all fans, including younger supporters, which the recent BBC Price of Football 2017 study highlighted. Overall, English Football League (EFL) figures show that junior season ticket sales have increased by 37% over the past 10 years with 20% of all EFL club match attendees now under 16 years old. Premier League clubs agreed last season to cap the cost of away tickets to £30 up until 2019, and clubs are helping more with concessions on travel.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-11-27T16:04:08.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792998/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792998/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792998/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-21","Sports: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment her department has made of the severity of the financial obstacles to youth attendance at professional sporting events; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","114783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792999","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-11-27","<p>Sport England is the arms-length body of government responsible for investing in and supporting grassroots sport and physical activity. As part of its 2017-21 investment round in national governing bodies (NGBs) of sport, Sport England has awarded over £225 million across 49 NGBs, with over £152 million to support NGB work on participation and over £73 million on NGB talent pathways.</p><p> </p><p>Where investment is not derived from Sport England exchequer or National Lottery funding, Sport England does not routinely collect information on the amount of investment into grassroots sport that professional clubs and other non-NGB organisations make.</p><p> </p><p>Details of the Exchequer and National Lottery awards that Sport England has made to all organisations since 2009 can be found here: https://www.sportengland.org/funding/our-investments-explained/investments-weve-made/</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-11-27T16:20:00.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792999/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792999/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/792999/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-11-21","Sports: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent estimate she has made of the level of investment in grassroots sport by professional clubs and bodies in the latest period for which figures are available; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","114784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793001","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-15","<p>The decision to remand an individual in custody or to grant bail is solely a matter for the courts acting in accordance with the law. Where an individual has a condition of bail to reside at a particular address and it transpires that he is not, or may not, be living at that address, the court may notify the police who will investigate whether or not there has been a breach of bail conditions. If there is evidence of an alleged breach the individual can be arrested and brought before the court. The court may then either remand the individual in custody or amend the bail conditions.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-12-15T12:34:30.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793001/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793001/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793001/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Bail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what action his Department requires courts to take upon being notified that a defendant has given an invalid or unavailable bail address to the court.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793002","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-28","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice (MOJ) comprises many organisations including Arm’s Length Bodies (ALBs). Each organisation holds separate contracts for these IT products and this information is not held or collated centrally.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-11-28T16:22:27.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793002/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793002/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793002/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Ministry of Justice: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department has spent on (a) phones, (b) computers and (c) iPads in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793003","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-28","<p>Maintaining order and control in our prisons is our priority and this large-scale project has been carefully managed. There is no evidence to link smoking as the causal factor in any incidents this year where national resources were deployed.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-28T17:32:31.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793003/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793003/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793003/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Prisons: Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prison disturbances have been linked to the ban on tobacco use on the prison estate in each prison facility since that ban was implemented.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793004","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-28","<p>The Prison Governors Association (PGA) made no representation on the banning of the use of tobacco on the prison estate.</p><p>Throughout the roll out, the PGA have been briefed regularly on the progress of the project including details of the prisons which sit in each phase of the roll out.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-28T17:34:25.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793004/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793004/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793004/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Prisons: Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department received representations from the Prison Governors Association on the banning of the use of tobacco on the prison estate; and if he will place a copy of any such representations in the Library.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793005","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-28","<p>There have been no representations received from Action on Smoking and Health (ASH) on the banning of the use of tobacco on the prison estate.</p><p> </p><p>The Director of ASH, Deborah Arnott is a member of the national smoke free prisons project board and is informed of the progress of the roll out.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-28T17:41:14.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793005/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793005/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793005/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Prisons: Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department received representations from Action on Smoking and Health on the banning of the use of tobacco on the prison estate; and if he will place a copy of any such representations in the Library.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793006","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-27","<p>Defra Commercial has not requested any specific information on sustainable procurement from the Ministry of Justice in the last year for the purpose of assessing that Department's performance against Government buying standards. Defra adheres to Government buying standards on sustainability and has incorporated them into its contracting terms and conditions. From September this year, Crown Commercial required all government departments to adhere to the ‘balanced scorecard’ approach to food procurement.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-11-27T17:28:51.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793006/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793006/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793006/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-21","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what information on sustainable procurement his Department has requested from the Ministry of Justice in the last year for the purpose of assessing his Department's performance against Government buying standards.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","114791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793007","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-29","<p>The Government remains fully committed to making all prisons smoke free. The decision to go smoke free in every prison is only taken after careful planning and preparation and the final decision is only taken when each prison has met stringent checks to ensure that it is safe to do so and all necessary healthcare support is available to help prisoners give up smoking.</p><p> </p><p>The national roll out of the Smoke Free Prisons project has been actively managed under usual project management disciplines.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-29T16:48:15.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793007/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793007/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793007/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Prisons: Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether a risk assessment was conducted by his Department on the smoking ban in prisons before the roll-out of that ban.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793008","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-28","<ul><li><p>Psychoactive substances are a significant driver of violence and instability in prisons. We have put in place a range of supply and demand reduction measures to address the availability and use of such harmful substances. This is based on a multi-agency approach working closely with health partners and law enforcement agencies. We are the first prison jurisdiction in the world to have developed a test for psychoactive substances, and have trained more than 300 sniffer dogs to specifically detect psychoactive substances. We have invested £3m in enhancing our intelligence capability to identify the organised crime groups and individuals behind supply routes, and are using this intelligence to work with the police to disrupt them.</p></li><li><p>Figures drawn from the HMPPS Incident Reporting System suggest there were just under 10,000 incidents where psychoactive substances were found in prisons between October 2015 and October 2017 in England and Wales. Data prior to October 2015 cannot be provided as this is when a new incident type was introduced to the Incident Reporting System.</p></li><li><p>Testing for psychoactive substances was only in place across the whole prison estate from September 2016 onwards. Between October 2016 and March 2017, there were 27,277 random mandatory drug tests administered. Each sample taken is tested for a range of illicit drugs, including psychoactive substances. As these are random drugs tests, prisoners tested in a single month are unique, but an individual prisoner could be chosen in multiple months. Figures for 2017/18 will be published in the Annual HMPPS Digest in July 2018.</p></li></ul>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","114794","2017-11-28T17:29:04.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793008/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793008/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793008/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Prisons: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the level of use of synthetic drugs in prisons in each of the the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793009","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-28","<ul><li><p>Psychoactive substances are a significant driver of violence and instability in prisons. We have put in place a range of supply and demand reduction measures to address the availability and use of such harmful substances. This is based on a multi-agency approach working closely with health partners and law enforcement agencies. We are the first prison jurisdiction in the world to have developed a test for psychoactive substances, and have trained more than 300 sniffer dogs to specifically detect psychoactive substances. We have invested £3m in enhancing our intelligence capability to identify the organised crime groups and individuals behind supply routes, and are using this intelligence to work with the police to disrupt them.</p></li><li><p>Figures drawn from the HMPPS Incident Reporting System suggest there were just under 10,000 incidents where psychoactive substances were found in prisons between October 2015 and October 2017 in England and Wales. Data prior to October 2015 cannot be provided as this is when a new incident type was introduced to the Incident Reporting System.</p></li><li><p>Testing for psychoactive substances was only in place across the whole prison estate from September 2016 onwards. Between October 2016 and March 2017, there were 27,277 random mandatory drug tests administered. Each sample taken is tested for a range of illicit drugs, including psychoactive substances. As these are random drugs tests, prisoners tested in a single month are unique, but an individual prisoner could be chosen in multiple months. Figures for 2017/18 will be published in the Annual HMPPS Digest in July 2018.</p></li></ul>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","114793","2017-11-28T17:29:04.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793009/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793009/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793009/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Prisons: Drug Seizures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many seizures of synthetic drugs there have been in each prison in each of the last 3 years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793010","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-29","<p>Any law enforcement or intelligence agency must represent the diverse communities it serves to enable them to gather the intelligence they need to keep us all safe. Diversity is therefore recognised as a crucial component of the intelligence agencies' workforce. The Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament recognised as much when they carried out an inquiry on Parliament's behalf into women in the intelligence agencies.</p><p>It has been the longstanding policy of successive Governments not to reveal details of the budgets or spending of the intelligence agencies. Statutory oversight for budgets and expenditure of the intelligence agencies is provided by the Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-11-29T14:13:37.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793010/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793010/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793010/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-21","GCHQ: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much GCHQ spent from the public purse on sponsorship of the National Diversity Awards 2017; and how many full-time equivalent GCHQ staff worked on that project.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793011","Home Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>Any law enforcement or intelligence agency must represent the diverse communities it serves, to enable them to gather the intelligence they need to keep us all safe. Diversity is therefore recognised as a crucial component of the intelligence agencies’ workforce. The Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament recognised as much when they carried out an inquiry on Parliament’s behalf into women in the intelligence agencies.</p><p> </p><p>It has been the longstanding policy of successive Governments not to reveal details of the budgets or spending of the intelligence agencies. Statutory oversight for this is provided by the Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-11-28T17:35:03.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793011/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793011/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793011/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-21","MI5","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much MI5 spent from the public purse on sponsorship of the National Diversity Awards 2017; and how many full-time equivalent MI5 staff worked on that project.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793012","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-11-29","<p>The Army sponsored the 'Positive Role Model for Race Award' at the National Diversity Awards at a cost of £9,995. No personnel were tasked to undertake a project relating to the awards, other than the minor task of arranging the sponsorship.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-11-29T15:52:01.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793012/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793012/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793012/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-11-21","Army","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much the Army spent from the public purse on sponsorship of the National Diversity Awards 2017; and how many full-time equivalent Army staff worked on that project.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793013","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-28","<p>The Government recognises the vital role that civil society plays in promoting democratic engagement and electoral registration. We will continue to work closely with such organisations, including to deliver National Democracy Week in July 2018.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-11-28T16:38:48.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793013/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793013/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793013/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-11-21","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent steps his Department has taken to encourage third sector organisations to help increase the level of electoral registration.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","114798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793014","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-28","<p>Any foreign national who comes to our country and abuses our hospitality by breaking the law should be in no doubt of our determination to deport them. Since 2010 more than 38,000 have been removed from prisons, Immigration Removal Centres and the community, and last year a record number of over 6,300 were removed.</p><p> </p><p>Information on convictions in England and Wales for these four nationalities is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost. However, information is available on the total number of foreign prisoners held by HM Prison and Probation Service in England and Wales; this can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/offender-management-statistics-quarterly-april-to-june-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/offender-management-statistics-quarterly-april-to-june-2017</a>. This information provides the total number of prisoners by nationality, with the total including unconvicted, convicted, and sentenced prisoners. In relation to convictions in Scotland and Northern Ireland, these are matters for the respective devolved administrations.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-28T17:32:10.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793014/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793014/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793014/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Convictions: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) Romanian, (b) Bulgarian, (c) Polish and (d) Croatian nationals were convicted of offences in the UK in each of the last 3 years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793015","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-12-01","<p>The table below shows the total value of criminal courts charge imposed, collected, cancelled and outstanding in England and Wales in the last 12 months</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Value Imposed</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Value Collected regardless of Imposition date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Value Legally Cancelled regardless of Imposition date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Value Administratively Cancelled regardless of Imposition date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Value Outstanding regardless of Imposition date</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year to 30/09/2017</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>7,099,073</p></td><td><p>1,694,221</p></td><td><p>203,853</p></td><td><p>35,614,174</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The criminal courts charge was introduced in April 2015 and applied to all adult offenders. It was abolished on 24 December 2015 but impositions prior to that date remained outstanding. HM Courts and Tribunals service actively manages all outstanding court ordered financial impositions and uses a number of intelligence tools to identify and implement suitable enforcement sanctions against those who fail to comply with the order. Outstanding amounts can be taken from the offender’s benefits or earnings or if this is not possible warrants can be issued to recover the amounts owed. HMCTS remains committed to finding new ways to ensure impositions are paid and to trace those who do not pay. This is why there has been year on year increase in the total amount of financial imposition collected over the last five years. The amount of financial imposition collected has risen from £381m at the end of 2015/16 to a record of £440 million at the end of 2016/17.</p><p> </p><p>Impositions can only be cancelled in one of two ways:</p><p>Legal cancellations which are at the direction of Judge or magistrate and are used where cases have been re-opened and the defendant has been found not guilty, following the presentation of additional information. Legal cancellations can be full or partial remittances of financial impositions.</p><p>Administrative cancellations which are non legal and can only be applied in very limited specific circumstances and in accordance with strict cancellation criteria for example when the defendant is deceased.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-12-01T10:54:35.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793015/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793015/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793015/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-21","Criminal Proceedings: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the value is of criminal courts charges that have (a) been levied, (b) been paid, (c) been written off and (d) remained outstanding in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793016","Home Office","false","2017-11-27","<p>Tackling knife crime is a priority for this Government. It is already an offence to threaten someone with a knife whether in public or on private property. On 14 October the Government launched a consultation on proposals for new laws in relation to offensive and dangerous weapons. The consultation document is open until 9 December and is available on the gov.uk website <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/offensive-and-dangerous-weapons-new-legislation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/offensive-and-dangerous-weapons-new-legislation</a></p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2017-11-27T17:30:15.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793016/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793016/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-21","Knives: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will extend the offence of threatening with a knife to incidents taking place on private property.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","114801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793017","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-27","<p>I visited Zimbabwe on 23 and 24 November to discuss Zimbabwe’s transition to democracy with actors from across the political spectrum. I stressed the importance of holding free and fair elections in line with the Zimbabwean Constitution and international standards. The UK has existing programmes promoting democratic and economic governance in Zimbabwe and we stand ready to support any new administration seeking to improve human rights, transparency and domestic accountability.​</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-11-27T16:01:44.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793017/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793017/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/793017/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-11-21","Zimbabwe: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what practical steps his Department is taking to ensure that the recent military intervention in Zimbabwe enables the restoration of democracy including multi-party elections.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","114802"
